name: Globular vase with cylindrical neck
description:
It concerns a large pot with narrow, cylindrical neck and globular belly. The vessel is further characterized by ribbon-shaped handles placed on a belly that is decorated with three horizontal belts, consisting of impressions made with a small toothed spatula. This epicardial vase was found by the Siret brothers during excavations in the southeast of Spain.  (Epicardial culture, 4500 BC - 3500 BC). Inv n.: PG.2833.1040

Find this object in the museum’s online catalog [Carmentis](https://www.carmentis.be:443/eMP/eMuseumPlus?service=ExternalInterface&module=collection&objectId=443018&viewType=detailView)
user.displayName: The Royal Museums of Art and History

name: Egg-shaped pot with small opening & flaring rim
description:
It concerns a type 4, egg-shaped pot in the typology of the El Argar culture of the Siret brothers, excavated in the southeast of Spain. These hand shaped vessels are associated with funerary contexts and are regularly found together with type 8 beakers. This type of ceramic is characterized by a dark, polished, metallic surface. This vessel is empty, but the associated file (PG) mentions 31 bone fragments and 2 teeth. (Argaric culture, 2300 BC - 1600 BC). Inv n.: PG.41.1.212

description:
It concerns a type 7 bowl on foot in the typology of the Siret brothers of the El Argar culture, excavated in the southeast of Spain. These hand shaped vessels are associated with funerary contexts and were probably reserved for females. This type of ceramic is characterized by a dark, polished, metallic surface. It concerns a type 5, biconical pot in the typology of the El Argar culture of the Siret brothers, excavated in the southeast of Spain. These hand shaped, carinated vessels are associated with funerary contexts and are regularly found together with type 3 bowls. This type of ceramic is characterized by a dark, polished, metallic surface. (Argaric culture, 2300 BC - 1600 BC). Inv n.: PG.41.1.112

name: Carinated vase with flaring rim - PG.2807.43
description:
It concerns a type 5, biconical pot in the typology of the El Argar culture of the Siret brothers, excavated in the southeast of Spain. These hand shaped, carinated vessels are associated with funerary contexts and are regularly found together with type 3 bowls. This type of ceramic is characterized by a dark, polished, metallic surface. In this case the upper part of the vase is taller than the base. (Argaric culture, 2300 BC - 1600 BC). Inv n.: PG.41.1.176

Find this object in the museum’s online catalog [Carmentis](https://www.carmentis.be:443/eMP/eMuseumPlus?service=ExternalInterface&module=collection&objectId=105904&viewType=detailView)

name: Thin-walled cup - PG.41.1.148
description:
It concerns a small tronconic vase with an unperforated protrusion at the height of the keel. This vessel comes from a Neolithic house discovered by the Siret brothers during excavations at Tres Cabezos in the southeast of Spain. (Almeria culture, Late neolithic 3500 BC - 2500 BC). Inv n.: PG.41.1.148

name: Bowl on foot - PG.41.1.223
description:
It concerns a type 7b bowl on foot in the typology of the Siret brothers of the El Argar culture, excavated in the southeast of Spain. These hand shaped vessels are associated with funerary contexts and were probably reserved for females. This type of ceramic is characterized by a dark, polished, metallic surface. In this case the foot has broken off. (Argaric culture, 2300 BC - 1600 BC). Inv n.: PG.41.1.223

name: 1935/4/GAL 1A y 1B Urna cineraria
description:
Título: Urna cineraria.
Descripción: Urna con cuerpo de perfil ovoide y borde dentado que encaja con la tapadera. Presenta decoración pintada de color rojizo.
Cultura: ibera.
Datación: siglos IV a III a.C.
Lugar de origen: Tútugi Galera (Granada).
Lugar actual: Museo Arqueológico Nacional (Madrid); inventario 1935/4/GAL 1A y 1B.
Fotografía: https://www.flickr.com/photos/elgolem/28823607124/
Método: Fotogrametría.
Modelo de la cámara: Nikon D7000 con objetivo Tamron 18-200 mm.
Software: Agisoft Photoscan Standard y MeshLab.
Más información: ver en CERES la urna
ver en CERES la tapadera
Agradecimientos: al Museo Arqueológico Nacional por las facilidades dadas para fotografiar esta pieza.

name: Oinochoe ibérico (Jumilla, Murcia)
description: Oinochoe con frisos engobados en blanco sobre los que se pinta la decoración con óxido rojo

name: Gefäß von der Heuneburg
description: Das bemalte Kegelhalsgefäß stammt von der Heuneburg, einer frühgeschichtlichen Höhensiedlung am Oberlauf der Donau (Landkreis Sigmaringen, Baden-Württemberg) und ist einer späten Phase der Hallstatt-Kultur zuzuordnen (6. Jh. v. Chr.). Heute gehört das Stück zur Sammlung der Abteilung für Jüngere Urgeschichte und Frühgeschichte der Universität Tübingen.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oală dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 p.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Cetate. Pentru acest orizont chronologic buza recipientului era evazată iar exteriorul vasului era împărțit în două registre. Un brâu crestat, aplicat la bombarea maximă a vasului, separa jumătățile oalei. Registrul superior era ornamentat cu „brăduți” incizați.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oală dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 a.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Observator. Oala de dimensiuni medii, cu buza invazată, modelată cu mâna, era ornamentată pe tot corpul vasului cu linii incizate, amintind de vasele celtice de tip situla contemporane.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oală dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 a.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Observator. Recipientul, modelat cu mâna, este ornamentat cu un șir de alveole imediat sub buză, iar pe perete cu doi butoni circulari, probabil cu rol de a împiedica alunecarea vasului la manipulare.

name: Fructieră dacică
description: Așa-numita „fructieră” era foarte probabil vasul destinat servirii mesei. Era modelat atât cu mâna cât și la roata olarului. De fapt era o strachină cu picior și avea buza lățită, ornamentată cu motive geometrice lustruite.

name: Ceașcă dacică
description: Ceașca dacică sau cățuia era un recipient utilizat la iluminarea spațiilor de locuit. De formă tronconică, mai rar fără toartă, ori prevăzut frecvent cu una, două sau chiar trei torți, cu capacitate variabilă, era modelat aproape exclusive cu mâna. Combustibilul era probabil grăsimea de origine animală.

name: Fructieră dacică
description: „Fructiera dacică” este un vasul pentru servirea mesei, emblematic pentru această civilizație. Vasele de mari dimensiuni, cu diametre de până la 60 cm, aveau un picior care compensa adesea absența mesei din unele locuințe dacice. Variantele, confecționate la roata olarului erau ornamentate cu motive lustruite sau pictate.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oală dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 a.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Observator. Vasul, modelat cu mâna, este ornamentat sub buză cu un ”val” simplu schematizat incizat, iar pe perete, puțin mai sus de zona median, cu patru butoni, doi circulari și doi piramidali. Probabil cei circulari erau cu rol de a împiedica alunecarea vasului din mâini la manipulare.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oală dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 a.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Observator. În acest secol recipientul, modelat cu mâna, era ornamentată pe tot corpul vasului, dar în acest caz doar cu patru butoni mici și patru mari cu alveoli amplasați la același nivel pe corpul vasului cu pereți drepți.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oală dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 a.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Observator. În acest secol recipientul, modelat cu mâna, era ornamentată pe tot corpul vasului, dar nu în exces. În cazul de față patru grupuri de câte trei linii oblice incizate erau despărțite de patru butoni plați. Aceștia aveau și rol de a împiedica alunecarea vasului din mâini la manipulare.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oala dacică, din primul secol al civilizației dacice clasice (sec. I a.Chr.) Este ornamentată pe tot corpul vasului, dar nu în exces. În recipientul modelat cu mâna era preparată o parte din hrană, prin fierbere.

name: Oala dacică
description: Oala din ultimul secol al regatului dac (sec. I p.Chr.), servea preparării hranei. Exteriorul vasului era împărțit în două registre ornamentale. Un brâu din alveole sau crestături, aplicat la bombarea maximă a vasului, separa jumătățile oalei.

name: Oala dacică.
description: Oala dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 p.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Cetate. Pentru acest orizont chronologic buza recipientului era evazată iar exteriorul vasului era împărțit în două registre. Un brâu crestat în relief, aplicat la bombarea maximă a vasului, separă jumătățile oalei.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oală dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 a.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Cetate. În acest secol recipientul, modelat cu mâna, era ornamentată pe tot corpul vasului cu patru grupuri de câte trei ghirlande incizate concentric despărțite de patru butoni plați.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oala din ultimul secol al regatului dac (sec. I p.Chr.), servea activității de preparare a hranei. De această dată exteriorul vasului era împărțit în două registre. Doar cel superior era ornamentat cu linii incizate sau „brăduți”. Un brâu din alveole sau crestături aplicat la bombarea maximă a vasului separa jumătățile oalei.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oala, din ultimul secol al regatului dac (sec. I p.Chr.), era destinată preparării mâncării. Un brâu din crestături, aplicat la bombarea maximă a vasului, separa jumătățile oalei. Doar cea superioară era ornamentată cu incizii. Buza evazată putea fi prevăzută cu alveole sau crestături.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oală dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 p.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Cetate. Pentru acest orizont chronologic buza recipientului era evazată iar exteriorul vasului era împărțit în două registre. Un brâu crestat în relief, aplicat la bombarea maximă a vasului, separă jumătățile oalei. La rândul său brâul este prevăzut cu patru pinteni ascuțiți, cu vârful în sus. Registrul superior este ornamentat cu ”val” multiplu incizat realizat imediat sub buza evazată.

name: Oală dacică
description: Oală dacică pentru preparat hrana (sec. 1 a.Chr.) descoperită la Șimleu Silvaniei-Cetate. Recipientul, modelat cu mâna, bombat, era ornamentată pe tot corpul vasului cu benzi de linii vertical incizate profund în pastă. Patru butoni cu alveole, amplasați sub buza puțin evazată, sporesc registrul ornamental al vasului.

name: Vas de provizii dacic
description: Așa numitul „vas de provizii”, chiupul, era modelat la roată sau cu mâna. Cele la roată erau ornamentate cu linii incizate. Era utilizat foarte probabil la stocarea apei, extreme de prețioasă în cetățile dacice amplasate pe dealuri, unde nu existau astfel de surse.

name: Visigothic Pottery, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain
description:
Ceramic jug of Visigothic tradition from the  site of  Oreto, Granátula de Calatrava,  Castilla-La Mancha, Spain.  Middle Ages (Islamic). In the collection of the Ciudad Real Museum.  Catalog number DO000254. Processed in Reality Capture from 554 images.

Urit	
8th-9th centuries AD


Citation:  Garcés, A.Mª.  & Romero, H. (2006):  Las cerámicas transicionales del siglo IX de Oreto-Zuqueca. Granátula de Calatyrava (Ciudad Real.).        aTempora Talavera de la Reina. Seis mil años de cerámica en Castilla-La Mancha’, 2018: 376"

This work is part of the collaboration agreement signed in 2020 between the Junta de Comunidades de Castilla-La Mancha and Global Digital Heritage for the digitization of the Cultural Heritage of Castilla-La Mancha region. We want to publicly thank the collaboration of the Museum of Ciudad Real, especially by its director José Ignacio de la Torre.

Ceramic jug with a handle from the  site of  Arroyo de las Lagunillas II, Ciudad Real,  Castilla-La Mancha, Spain.  Visigoth. In the collection of the Ciudad Real Museum.  Catalog number DO000289. Processed in Reality Capture from 495 images. 

This work is part of the collaboration agreement signed in 2020 between the Junta de Comunidades de Castilla-La Mancha and Global Digital Heritage for the digitization of the Cultural Heritage of Castilla-La Mancha region. We want to publicly thank the collaboration of the Museum of Ciudad Real, especially by its director José Ignacio de la Torre.

name: Pisside attica, 470-460 a.C., MANAM
description:
Da Sirolo-Numana, Loc Molinelli
470-460 a.C.
La pisside è un contenitore usato per riporre cosmetici e altre suppellettili della sfera muliebre, che spesso veniva deposto nelle sepolture, quale segno distintivo delle dame di alto lignaggio. L'esemplare qui esposto, di straordinaria fattura, narra con accenti di delicata poesia il miracoloso evento della nascita di Afrodite: è una rara pisside a fondo bianco di eccezionale raffinatezza, dove è rappresentata una scena sostanzialmente inedita dal punto di vista iconografico.
Per tali ragioni, questo pezzo di maestria esecutiva attribuito al Pittore dello Splanchnoptes e datato al 460 a.C., è un documento pressoché unico nella produzione ceramica attica. 

Con la collaborazione di Museo Archeologico Nazionale delle Marche

name: Apulian Vessel 300-400BC
description:
3D Reconstruction of a small Apulian Attic Vase from about 300BC using 3DF Zephyr photogrammetry software.  213 photos were used.

This vase was excavated and brought to the United Staes just prior to WWI by Henry Draper, a superintendent in the Washington, DC school system for whom the Draper School on "K" Street was named.  It's about 140mm tall, and was apparently found in pieces and reconstructed.

name: Aryballos
description:
Aryballos cu figuri negre lucrat la roată din pastă fină, folosit pentru păstrarea uleiurilor parfumate. A fost descoperit într-un loc necunoscut (passim) din zona Mangaliei, în 1947.
Tipul de vas aryballos cu figuri negre a apărut în Corinth în sec. VIII-VI a.Chr. Varianta cu corpul globular se circumscrie ceramicii attice produsă între sfârșitul sec. VI și începutul sec. IV a.Chr.

Piesa se află în colecția Muzeului Județean „Teohari Antonescu”, din Giurgiu.

name: Kantharos
description:
Vas grecesc din necropola geto-dacică de la Zimnicea, descoperit în 1967. Piesa a fost încadrată de autorul descoperirii (A.D. Alexandrescu) în sec. al IV-lea a.Chr.

Piesa se află în colecția Muzeului Județean „Teohari Antonescu”, din Giurgiu.

name: Crater with volutes (vase)
description:
Crater with volutes, around 400-390 BC J. - C., Apulian production of Tarente (Southern Italy), attributed to the painter of the Birth of Dionysos, would come from Bari, ceramics. Musée d'Art et d'Histoire (musée du Cinquantenaire, Brussels, Belgium). Made with ReMake and ReCap Pro from AutoDesk.

Originally a vase for mixing wine and water at the banquet, the monumental Apulian craters, like this one, seem to have been created for a funeral use. The scene represented here reflects this function: after his death, Heracles is brought to Olympus in the chariot of Athena, her protective goddess. The welcome of the hero in the domain of the gods signals his immortal status.

The painter of the Birth of Dionysis is one of the leading figures of the ornate style, one of the leading artists of ancient Apulian. He paints sophisticated compositions in a rich style, often on large vases.

For more updates, please consider to follow me on Twitter at @GeoffreyMarchal.

name: Mini Skyphos Cup
description:
This small skyphos cup ([GR.54.1865](http://data.fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk/id/object/65806)) was found at a classical cemetery at Kranioi in Cephalonia, a Greek Island near Corinth, Greece and dates from 500 B.C. — 401 B.C. A skyphos is a deep-bowled drinking vessel with a low foot and two short handles, and these minature versions are found in Corinthian pottery production during this period. These cups are often found at sanctuaries, suggesting their use as votive offerings throughout the region.


This 3D model was made as part of the [#CEEF3D project ](http://creative-economy.fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk/) at the Fitzwilliam Museum, in connection to [Being an Islander: Art and Identity of the large Mediterranean Islands](http://www.fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk/being-islander-art-and-identity-large-mediterranean-islands).

name: Midden-Geometrische Pyxis (850-760 v.Chr.)
description:
Afmetingen:

Breedte: 20,5 cm 

Lengte: 18,5 cm (met deksel)

Diameter: 17 cm    

Wanddikte: 5 mm     
      
De gebruikscontext van pyxides is omstreden, het is echter waarschijnlijk dat pyxides olie of een set sieraden bevatte. Er zijn zelden pyxides gevonden in nederzettingscontext. Meestal worden ze gevonden in grafcontext, vaak in de graven van (rijke) vrouwen.

Parallellen zijn gevonden in een graf in Kerameikos, Athene. Ook bekend als The Potters' Quarter: het productiecentrum voor Attisch aardewerk. Het is waarschijnlijk dat de pyxis uit onze collectie ook van Attische makelij is.

De datering is gebaseerd op typologie, maar valt lastig exact te plaatsen: pyxides zijn vaak in verschillende stijlen binnen dezelfde context te vinden

Vondstnummers: -Arch 602.2/vH2 
                             -Arch 602.3/vH2

Voor meer informatie over pyxides, zie referentie:

Bohen, B. (1988). Die geometrischen Pyxiden. Berlin: De Gruyter

name: Apulische Amphore

Auf der anderen Seite des Gefäßes sieht man einen nach rechts gewandten, auf einem Felsen sitzenden Eros. Die geflügelte Personifikation der Liebe ist reich geschmückt.

name: Apulian Red-Figured Lebes Gamikos
description: Culture: Greek Material: Ceramic Dims: H 19.3 Accession No: HCM 234 Current Location: The Hunt Museum Limerick Lebes gamikos are distinct Greek wedding gifts for the bride. A woman seated on a rock cradles a dish and a winged Eros, clutching a mirror in his right hand form the scenes. Both have rounded bodies, necklaces, bracelets and anklets. Eros wears a beaded bandolier. Yellow and white colour is added. In wedding scenes, lebes contain branches of myrtle, symbols of fertility and joy. This vase has a slim body, two upright handles and a lid with an elongated finial. The shoulder is decorated with rays, bands of wave pattern surround the body and lid, and below the handles are composite palmettes. Red figure painting was an invention of the Athenians in the sixth-century BC. South Italian Greek colonies, including Apulia continued vase production after its decline in Athens. [More](http://www.huntmuseum.com/collection/apulian-red-figured-lebes-gamikos/)

name: Romeinse deukbeker RBA14p V402
description: Hoogte ca. 13,3 cm, diameter rand ca. 10 cm

name: Alice Holt Jar
description:
Everyday life in Pontes, Roman Staines – an Alice Holt food storage jar. ‘Alice Holt’ sounds like the Roman version of ‘Clarice Cliff’, but is actually a place, a wood near Farnham on the Hampshire/Surrey border. Roman potteries in the area produced enormous quantities of what is unkindly termed ‘grey coarse ware’. Alice Holt jars and dishes are found extensively in the South East of England, and by the 4th century it accounts for 70% of all the pottery found at Staines.

Our jar was reconstructed in the 1980s and the ‘new’ plaster parts crudely painted grey in an attempt to match the original. If we were doing this today the new parts would be left ‘virgin’ and clearly distinct from the original. Sitting on the back shelf of the ‘Roman shop’ in the museum, it gives a good impression of what would be sitting on shelves in most houses of the time. Reading museum have a rather beautiful complete version of this jar on display.

Our jar stands 196mm high, 151mm outer rim diameter, 118mm inner rim diameter, 127mm

name: Samian Dish
description:
Life and death in Pontes, Roman Staines – a Samian dish found in a grave. This small Samian dish was found in a cremation burial pit from the 2nd century AD and was found upside down over the ashes. The leaf and vine design we see on its rim is called en-barbotine; a clay slip was used to coat the object and create the design. This cremation was found at the Old Police Station in Staines, which is a little way outside of the Roman town, the custom for adult burials. 

In addition to this near perfect Samian dish, a pair of beautiful enamelled brooches, a glass dish, a wine flagon and two small glass bottles were also found in the grave. Whoever was buried here was much loved and was buried with treasured objects for the afterlife. All of these items are on display in Spelthorne Museum.

Many thanks to the student volunteers from Royal Holloway College for their work on this model.

name: Roman Baby Bottle
description:
Purchased as a ‘Roman baby feeding bottle’ at auction and then gifted to the museum by the purchaser. Identification currently under investigation. Note the two (old) broken sections on the top where a handle would have attached. This would make it very similar to a Spanish botijo wine cooler.

This is our second attempt at photogrammetry on this object. The results are far superior to our first effort since we now understand how to sequence the photography. We also have a new camera; a Canon EOS2000D with a 50mm EF lens (effective 80mm focal length) used at F22. Many thanks to the student volunteers from Royal Holloway College, London, for their help with this work.

name: JC-79-193 Terra Sigillata, Drangendorff 37
description:
Taça de *terra sigillata*, produzida na Hispânia, provavelmente no século II,  desconhecendo-se a oficina de origem. A *terra  sigillata* é um tipo de cerâmica da época romana. O nome deriva do selo (*sigilum*) com que os recipientes eram marcados, identificando o oleiro ou oficina onde eram produzidos. Este exemplar restaurado pertence ao Acervo da Coleção Arqueológica José Coelho, sendo proveniente do Castro do Banho (S. Pedro do Sul, Viseu).

ÉPOCA/PERIOD Romana/Roman

PROVENIÊNCIA/SOURCE [Castro do Banho](https://umap.openstreetmap.fr/en/map/mapa-da-galeria-3d_543623#17/40.73883/-8.09895) (S. Pedro do Sul)

ACERVO/COLLECTION  Coleção Arqueológica José Coelho, JC-79-193

MEDIDAS/MEASUREMENTS (mm) 110 (height), 120 (aperture diameter)

name: Waldling | Upper Austria – Terra Sigillata
description:

Julianus I

name: "Megarian" Sigillata Bowl
description:
Location: Museo Archeologico di Aidone, Aidone, Sicily, Italy

Catalogue Number: 83-167

Description: "Megarian" Sigillata bowl decorated with relief outside

Data Capture Method: Photogrammetry

Processing Software: Reality Capture

Citation: The data for this project were originally collected as a joint effort between the University of Catania and CVAST at the University of South Florida (USF), with the collaboration of the Fondazione Bruno Kessler (FBK). Dr. Mariarita Sgarlata and Dr. Herbert Maschner, Principal Investigators. We gratefully acknowledge the participation of the administrators of the Villa Romana del Casale and the Museo Archeologico di Aidone. The data have been transferred to Global Digital Heritage (GDH) for processing and analysis. Funding for this project, both at USF and at GDH, has been provided by the Hitz Foundation, Herbert Maschner, Principal Investigator.

name: Roman Barbotine Beaker
description:
Culture: [Roman](http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300020541) Material: Ceramic Dims: H 8.2cm Accession No: MG 137B Current Location: [The Hunt Museum](https://www.huntmuseum.com/) [Limerick](https://www.geonames.org/7778675/limerick-city.html) A bag-shaped beaker with rounded profile, slightly incurved conical base, narrow foot and cornice rim. A fine white ware with black coating decorated with a trailed slip ([barbotine](http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300257360) technique) of raised motifs, a hound chasing a hare, dots and frieze of leaves. This is [Cologne](http://www.geonames.org/2886242/koeln.html) ware dating to the second or third-century AD with a distribution in the Rhineland and Britain.
[More](http:///www.huntmuseum.com/collection/castor-ware-cup):

name: Ceramic Jar, Dibba Al Hisn, Sharjah
description:
Glazed ceramic jar. 1st Century CE. Specimen from the collection excavated from a communal tomb of the Roman-Parthian period in Dibba Al Hisn, Sharjah (Jasim 2006). Part of the museum exhibit for Madrid, Spain (Córdoba 2016:124, Figure 161). Catalogue No. EXS 185, DIB23.

Sabah A. Jasim. 2006. Trade centres and commercial routes in the Arabian Gulf: Post-Hellenistic discoveries at Dibba, Sharjah, United Arab Emirates. Arabian Archaeology and Epigraphy 2006: 17: 214–237.

J. Mª Córdoba 2016. La era de Mleiha: navegantes y caravanas antes del Islam. Pp 83-130 (Figure p. 92). In EN LOS CONFINES DE ORIENTE PRÓXIMO: El hallazgo moderno del país de Magán. Museo Arqueológico Nacional Catálogo de la Exposición Temporal Celebrada entre el 18 de abril y el 29 de mayo de 2016. Comisario: J. Mª Córdoba Zoilo. Comisarias adjuntas: C. del Cerro Linares, Mª C. Pérez Díe, E. Pons Mellado.

name: Lucerna Lamp ME5048 Evora Portugal
description:
Roman clay lamp (lucerna) of unknown origin. Lamps fueled with olive oil and other vegetable oils were very common in the Roman world to provide artificial light. It is decorated with barely noticeable and unidentified vegetal elements. The specimen presents 5,2 cm in height and 10,6 cm in long. It is currently preserved in the Frei Manuel do Cenáculo National Museum (Évora, Portugal). Catalog No. ME5048.

587 photos from Canon 5D Mk IV. Completely processed (aligned, scaled, meshed, cleaned, simplified, unwrapped, textured) in Reality Capture. SOUSA, J.J. Rigaud de - "Inventário de materiais para a arqueologia bracarense" in Bracara Augusta, vol. XX, nº 43-44 (55-56). Braga: 1966, pp. 165–178.

name: Lucerna Lamp ME5047 Evora, Portugal
description:
Roman clay lamp (lucerna) dated between the 1st century AD and the 3rd century AD, of unknown origin. Lamps fueled with olive oil and other vegetable oils were very common in the Roman world to provide artificial light. It is decorated with a winged victory, front, standing on a globe (Ferreira de Almeida). Her left hand is raised with a crown and on her left she holds a palm leaf. Lucerne of scrolls type Bailey D-v, Dressel 12/13, Deneauve V B. The specimen presents 2,8 cm in height and 10,4 cm in long. It is currently preserved in the Frei Manuel do Cenáculo National Museum (Évora, Portugal). Catalog No. ME5047.

475 photos from Canon 5D Mk IV. Completely processed (aligned, scaled, meshed, cleaned, simplified, unwrapped, textured) in Reality Capture. FERREIRA DE ALMEIDA, José Antonio - "Introdução ao estudo das lucernas em Portugal" in O Arqueólogo Português, Nova Série, II. Lisboa: 1953.

description:
Roman clay lamp (lucerna) of unknown origin. Lamps fueled with olive oil and other vegetable oils were very common in the Roman world to provide artificial light. Straight base engraved with two circles, between which a dotted row appears, in the center a cross of straight arms with a small circle in each quadrant. The specimen presents 5,5 cm in height and 9,5 cm in long. It is currently preserved in the Frei Manuel do Cenáculo National Museum (Évora, Portugal). Catalog No. ME5036.

name: Lucerna Lamp ME5028 Evora, Portugal
description:
Roman clay lamp (lucerna) dated between the 1st century AD and the 2nd century AD, of unknown origin. Lamps fueled with olive oil and other vegetable oils were very common in the Roman world to provide artificial light. It is decorated with two heads, the left one represents a glabrous man, and the right one a bearded profile man. Between them is a vase. Irregular base with an engraved ring and potter's mark: "CO PPI.RES (p has a dot on top), abbreviated form of C. Oppi (us) Res (titutus). Bailey Type B-iii, Dressel 11, Deneauve VA. The specimen presents 2,5 cm in height and 9,4 cm in long. It is currently preserved in the Frei Manuel do Cenáculo National Museum (Évora, Portugal). Catalog No. ME5028.

588 photos from Canon 5D Mk IV. Completely processed (aligned, scaled, meshed, cleaned, simplified, unwrapped, textured) in Reality Capture. FERREIRA DE ALMEIDA, José Antonio - "Introdução ao estudo das lucernas em Portugal" in O Arqueólogo Português, Nova Série, II. Lisboa: 1953, p. 155.

name: Roman Ceramic Pot, Curral dos Cães, Portugal
description:
This a roman pot from the archaeological site of Curral dos Cães, in the Montemor-o-Novo region - Portugal. The site was discovered during agricultural works, revealing several habitational structures.

This piece is part of the collection at the Museum of São Domingos, Montemor-o-Novo.

name: Ceramic Pitcher, Cucufate, Portugal
description:
Pitcher from roman villa of S. Cucufate, Alentejo, Portugal. High Roman Empire (1st century AD to 2nd century AD). Roman common-ware pottery. Tall vase, crouching down to the bottom. Smooth exterior surfaces without any decoration. This specimen presents 17 cm in height  and 13,4 cm in diameter. Currently it is exposed in the permanent exhibition of the museum of S. Cucufate (Vila de Frades, Vidigueira). Catalog No. CUC. 80 2141. Processed and modeled in Reality Capture from 612 photos. 

ALARCÃO, Jorge de, Robert Étienne, Françoise Mayet (colaboração de J.-P. Bost, G. Charpentier, V. Mantas, I. Pereira e P. Sillières), (1990): Les villas romaines de S. Cucufate (Portugal), Paris.

name: Roman Pot,  Montemor-o-Novo, Portugal
description: A small roman pot discovered in the historical urban part of Montemor-o-Novo, Portugal. It is not a common find in the city, although there are several roman sites identified around the city. This pot is made in a red clay that is very typical from Montemor-o-Novo.

name: Roman Lamp, Cucufate, Portugal
description: Clay lamp (lucerna) from roman villa of S. Cucufate, Alentejo, Portugal. High Roman Empire (2nd century AD). Lamps fueled with olive oil and other vegetable oils were very common in the Roman world to provide artificial light. This specimen has a shoulder decorated with an undetermined motif (maybe pearls or ovules) and separated from the disk by a two-line frame. The filling-hole appears in the center of the disc (discus). The specimen presents 2,3 cm in height  and 7 cm in long. Currently it is exposed in the permanent exhibition of the museum of S. Cucufate (Vila de Frades, Vidigueira). Catalog No. CUC. 81 203. Processed and modeled in Reality Capture from 588 photos

name: Late Roman Cup, Cucufate, Portugal
description:
Cup from roman villa of S. Cucufate, Alentejo, Portugal. Late Roman Empire (4th century AD to 5th century AD). Its corresponds to the third occupation phase of the villa. This kind of pottery was used to serve and consume food. Decoration composed of geometric motifs. This specimen is 11.2 cm in height and 20 cm in diameter. Currently it is displayed in the permanent exhibition of the museum of S. Cucufate (Vila de Frades, Vidigueira). Catalog No. CUC. 80 1829. Processed and modeled in Reality Capture from 492 photos. 

ALARCÃO, Jorge de, Robert Étienne, Françoise Mayet (colaboração de J.-P. Bost, G. Charpentier, V. Mantas, I. Pereira e P. Sillières), (1990): Les villas romaines de S. Cucufate (Portugal), Paris.

name: Roman Bowl, Cucufate, Portugal
description:
Bowl from roman villa of S. Cucufate, Alentejo, Portugal. Roman Empire (1st century AD to 5th century AD). Roman common-ware pottery.  The bowl was used essentially for the individual consumption of liquid and semi-liquid foods. This specimen is 5 cm in height and 17.4 cm in diameter. Currently it is displayed in the permanent exhibition of the museum of S. Cucufate (Vila de Frades, Vidigueira). Catalog No. CUC. 80 97. Processed and modeled in Reality Capture from 549 photos. 

VAZ PINTO, I., (1999): A Cerâmica Comum de S. Cucufate, Partes I-III, Parte IV, Tese de Doutoramento na área de Pré-História e Arqueologia a apresentar ao Departamento de História da Universidade Lusíada, Lisboa. 

VAZ PINTO, I., (2003): A cerâmica comum das villae romanas de São Cucufate (Beja), Lisboa.

name: Roman Cup, Cucufate, Portugal
description:
Cup from roman villa of S. Cucufate, Alentejo, Portugal. High Roman Empire (1st century AD). It corresponds to an importation of the time of the Flavian dynasty (from 69 AD to 96 AD), and thus, is contemporary of the occupation of the first villa. This kind of pottery were used to serve and consume food. This specimen presents 10.8 cm in height  and 25 cm in diameter. Currently it is showcased in the permanent exhibition of the museum of S. Cucufate (Vila de Frades, Vidigueira). Catalog No. CUC. 83 3708. Processed and modeled in Reality Capture from 437 photos.

name: Roman Patera from Ilidža, Bosnia
description:
Roman patera found at Ilidža near Sarajevo, Bosnia. 2nd century AD. 

Data were collected as part of a joint research project between GDH and the Association for the Digitization and Informatisation of Cultural Heritage (DIGI.BA) in Sarajevo, in full collaboration with The Sarajevo Museum. Scanned artifacts were on display. Model was created from 509 images from a Canon 5D mk IV. All data were processed in Reality Capture. Project ID RomanPottery.

name: Roman Jar (Fonte da Senhora 7, Montemor-o-Novo)
description: This an archaeological find, in common pottery, from Fonte da Senhora 7, a roman necropolis, in Montemor-o-Novo (Portugal) and is part of the collection of the Archaeological Museum of Montemor-o-Novo. 402 Photos from Canon 5D Mk IV (35mm lens). Currently it is exposed in the permanent exhibition of the museum of S. Cucufate (Vila de Frades, Vidigueira). Catalog No. CUC. 01 3064. Processed and modeled in Reality Capture from 391 photos.

name: Jar, Roman Villa, Cucufate, Portugal
description:
Jug from roman villa of S. Cucufate, Alentejo, Portugal. Late Antiquity (Probably 6th century AD or 7th century AD.). Narrow neck ritual jug, with flat bottom and ocher paste with orange outer shell. This specimen comes from Sepultura 2, a wooden sarcophagus placed inside a brick box, located on the perimeter of the ancient Roman temple that was later  transformed into a place of Christian worship. It contained the skeleton of an adult man, two rings, two shoe soles, a dolabra, and a jug. The grave was intact, so the findings correspond to the offerings made at the time of burial. The piece is displayed in the permanent exhibition of the museum of S. Cucufate (Vila de Frades, Vidigueira). Catalog No. CUC. 83 4611 (T2). Processed and modeled in Reality Capture from 489 photos

ALARCÃO, Jorge de, Robert Étienne, Françoise Mayet (colaboração de J.-P. Bost, G. Charpentier, V. Mantas, I. Pereira e P. Sillières), (1990): Les villas romaines de S. Cucufate (Portugal), Paris.

name: Roman Cup, Potters Mark, Cucufate, Portugal
description: Cup from roman villa of S. Cucufate, Alentejo, Portugal. High Roman Empire (1st century AD to 2nd century AD). It is an imported ceramic (potter's mark - C.A.H. – inside). This kind of pottery was used to serve and consume food. This specimen is 4.8 cm in height  and 9.5 cm in diameter. Currently it is displayed in the permanent exhibition of the museum of S. Cucufate (Vila de Frades, Vidigueira). Catalog No. CUC. 83 5230. Processed and modeled in Reality Capture from 431 photos.

name: Roman lucerne,  Fonte da Senhora 7, Portugal
description: Description of the archaeological site: Fonte da Senhora 7, a roman necropolis, in Montemor-o-Novo (Portugal). This archaeological piece is part of the collection of the Archaeological Museum of Montemor-o-Novo. This roman lucerne is of late production, dating from the 3rd to the 4th century AD. Characterized by its round spout slightly protruding from the rest of the lucerne body. This artefact, which is not very common in the region of Montemor-o-Novo, comes from the archeological site of the Necropolis of Fonte da Senhora 7 - a Roman-Late Burial Site (4th century AD) in the area of the Minutos Dam, excavated in 2001, where there were found fifteen graves excavated in the rock with associated funeral archaeological pieces.
